            <!-- Contents -->
            <noteGrp type="workDesc">
               <note type="description">Using the same format as Sulamī’s book Maqāmāt
                     al-awliyāʾ, a book of adab, with many stories from al-Andalus and people that
                     IA knew.</note>
               <note type="structure"/>
               <note type="contentsNote"/>
            </noteGrp>
            <!-- Stemmatics -->
            <note type="stemmatics">A much copied work, of which there are no historic mss,
                  although Ahmad III A2415 is dated 712H. Brocklemann, according to OY, thinks it is
                  apocryphal and should be attributed to Dhahabī (d.748) (see OY p. 397). But there
                  is textual evidence that it is by IA: Claude Addas, in her biography of IA Quest
                  for the Red Sulphur (Cambridge, 1993), refers to several passages where incidents
                  are described which correspond to information in other verified texts; eg. pp.
                  211, 223, 227. Also, a work of this title is mentioned in both the lists which IA
                  made of his own works, Fihris muʾallafāt al-shaykh al-akbar (RG142) and Ijāza
                  li-l-malik al-Muẓaffar (RG 269). Michel Chodkiewicz relates that some years ago he
                  saw an autograph copy, written in Malatya, which is in private ownership in
                  Tunisia, but we have not yet been able to obtain a copy of this. Other mss
                  identified: Ragib Pasha 1204 (944H); Veliyuddin 2573 ff. 1-275 (945H); Düğümlü
                  Baba 392 (950H)</note>
